 RESP2 protocol for all connection tests. It looks like I should check the existing Redis URI and client options to ensure they assert this protocol. Maybe I'll create a helper function to build the client with specific options, like setting auto-reconnect to false. I want to confirm that it's covering the necessary areas and that I'm avoiding deprecated APIs. I’m also thinking of implementing the HELLO response to test new behavior with the protocol versions.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Inspecting Redis HELLO response**\\n\\nThe Redis HELLO response in the RESP3 protocol is a map that begins with the '%' character. I think it’s a good idea to take a closer look at the GenericMapOutput to understand how it handles this format. I'm curious how the state machine processes this and whether it can effectively manage the map response. Getting a solid grasp on this will help me ensure everything aligns with the expected behavior of the protocol.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_ogkGfq166kw1EWGELdTeyKeQ|fc_04a624cccdb0beed016a234ab3e9e08194ac5b0adf085a9903", "name": "read", "arguments": {"path": "/home/vjovanov/c/forge/forge2/graalvm-reachability-metadata/forge/local_repositories/source_context/io.lettuce/lettuce-core/6.2.6.RELEASE/main/extracted/io/lettuce/core/output/GenericMapOutput.java", "limit": 160}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 896, "output": 328, "cacheRead": 31232, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 32456, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780697766522, "responseId": "resp_04a624cccdb0beed016a234aa6f6848194946384de3596823d"}, "toolResults": [{"role": "toolResult", "toolCallId": "call_ogkGfq166kw1EWGELdTeyKeQ|fc_04a624cccdb0beed016a234ab3e9e08194ac5b0adf085a9903", "toolName": "read", "content": [{"type": "text", "text": "/*\n * Copyright 2019-2022 the original author or authors.\n *\n * Licensed und